Chamaecytisus palmensis

    Authority
      Family
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 11660

   Notes
   DESCRIPTION: Leguminous shrub or small tree which grows to a height of
   5-6 m and almost to the same crown diameter. It has long drooping
   branches with dull, bluish-green trifoliate leaves. On deep sands,
   roots can penetrate to 10 m and more. Inflorescences white. Seed pods
   black, flattened, up to 5 cm long. USE: Used as fodder (cut and carry)
   and for grazing. In dry regions as a windbreak and shelter belt. It has
   dense wood with a specific gravity of 0.7 useful as firewood. Annual DM
   production of range from 13-18 t/ha in New Zealand to 5-10 t/ha in
   Ethiopia. The edible DM of leaf and fine stem will be 50-60% of this
   range. GROWING PERIOD: Perennial. COMMON NAMES: Tagasaste, Tree
   lucerne, False tree Lucerne. FURTHER INF: It is native of the Canary
   Isles. It has become naturalized and/or utilized in several temperate
   countries, e.g. New Zealand, in regions with Mediterranean-type
   climates, e.g. Western Australia, and in countries with long hot, dry
   summers, e.g. Ethiopia. It grows well in a rainfall range of 350-1600
   mm. Suited to drought-prone sandy soils.

   Sources
   [10]Grassland Index
   Steven R and Staberg P 2005
   Frame J 2005

